#=GF DR   SO; 0000417; polypeptide_domain;
#=GF CC   This family, many of whose members are YcbG, organises the
#=GF CC   macrodomain Ter of the chromosome of bacteria such as E coli. In
#=GF CC   these bacteria, insulated macrodomains influence the segregation
#=GF CC   of sister chromatids and the mobility of chromosomal DNA.
#=GF CC   Organisation of the Terminus region (Ter) into a macrodomain
#=GF CC   relies on the presence of a 13 bp motif called matS repeated 23
#=GF CC   times in the 800-kb-long domain. MatS sites are the main targets
#=GF CC   in the E. coli chromosome of YcbG or MatP (macrodomain Ter
#=GF CC   protein). MatP accumulates in the cell as a discrete focus that
#=GF CC   co-localises with the Ter macrodomain. The effects of MatP
#=GF CC   inactivation reveal its role as the main organiser of the Ter
#=GF CC   macrodomain: in the absence of MatP, DNA is less compacted, the
#=GF CC   mobility of markers is increased, and segregation of the Ter
#=GF CC   macrodomain occurs early in the cell cycle. A specific
#=GF CC   organisational system is required in the Terminus region for
#=GF CC   bacterial chromosome management during the cell cycle. This
#=GF CC   entry represents the N-terminal domain of MatP.
